Apple announced a major shift from IBM to Intel chips for its Macintosh machines, ending a 14-year alliance.
This move aims to enhance performance, lower costs, and attract more developers.
CEO Steve Jobs expressed confidence in Intel's technology for creating top-notch personal computers.
The transition is expected to be completed by 2007, with Intel processors becoming standard in all Mac products.
This decision marks a significant change for Apple, aligning it with industry standards and potentially expanding its market share.
The move has implications for software developers and signals a new era for Apple's hardware technology.
